{
  "doc_id": "39309",
  "text": "Another method of analysis, estimating coherence/synchronization, is an example of a technique that could improve classification of MCI. Coherence analysis is widely used and represents a normalized linear measure of the correlations between two signals as a function of frequency [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . There is a decrease in coherence values in alpha and beta bands in AD patients (for a review, see [CITATION_3] ). In the case of MCI, there is a decrease of intrahemispheric frontoparietal EEG coherence and an increase of temporal interhemispheric coherence compared to elderly controls. [CITATION_4] . Synchronization likelihood (SL) [CITATION_5] has been used to study the brain activity in MCI, and was found to be significantly decreased in the 14-18 and 18-22 Hz bands in AD patients compared with both MCI subjects and healthy controls [CITATION_6] . Unfortunately, SL was similar in the controls and MCI patients.",
